alternate realities' should affect in any way its status in our world. This is obviously an unintended effect. But by and large, most of the problems stem from simple lack of foresight when designing quests, not taking into account the possibility of the TLC (see dead horse above). It is these problems that most need to be addressed. But the nodrop problem IS a coding thing which should therefore be easy to fix (and that would fix MANY things), and I find the lack of fixing THAT fairly inexcuseable.<br><br>No, the TLC doesn't affect me. That's really irrelevant to me. I dislike it on principle: we 'signed up' for a server with a set of rules, but there is an implied agreement there that those rules would actually be supported, that problems would be addressed (preferably before one's children age 20 years and have children of their own). But if they aren't going to commit the resources to doing it right, then they have violated the spirit of their agreement with us when we came here. No, there is nothing that says they must fix bugs, or limit downtime, or anything at all really. Legally, they are certainly secure. But right is right, and wrong is wrong, and legal or not, enticing people to a server knowing that they will experience problems that will never be fixed, well, that's just wrong in my book.<br><br>If the only man-hour-effective way to fix all the problems is to remove the TLC, that's fine. If they want to keep it and address the problems, that's even better, however doubtful. If removing it means making nodrop items nodrop again, that's fine too, and since that is the codebase of the bulk of the servers, then there are not apt to be any unforeseen problems that would go unrectified. I'm really pretty flexible. But the one thing I DON'T want is a rule in the ruleset - any rule - that doesn't receive reasonable support when problems arise. I think that's imminently reasonable.<br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=